Introduction: With the development of the COVID-19, the south China seafood market has almost been identified as the source of the outbreak, although the current whereabouts of the wild animals sold before the market's closure are unknown, wuhan officials did not make any disclosure.

By Tong Lan

With the COVID-19 tracing effort underway, the south China Seafood Market is almost certainly the source of the outbreak, although the current whereabouts of the wildlife sold before the market's closure are unknown, wuhan officials did not make any disclosure.

The Chinese Center for Disease Control and Prevention recently disclosed that the institute has made a step forward in COVID-19 research, first collecting 585 environmental samples from the South China Seafood Market in Wuhan, thirty-three samples were found to contain COVID-192019-ncov nucleic acid and the virus was successfully isolated from positive environmental samples.

The ban on wildlife trade is only a temporary measure

The early detection of the COVID-19 outbreak in Wuhan is closely linked to the south China Seafood Market in Wuhan. Tracing the source of the virus, controlling the source and elucidating the virus intermediate host are the key links to control the virus from animal to human.

"The virus may have come from wild animals in the seafood market, although the exact source has not yet been determined, " Takatomi, an academician and director of the Chinese Center for Disease Control and Prevention, said on Jan. 22, or a special permit may be required, but legal restrictions on certain species may be relaxed if they are raised commercially.

After the outbreak of Public Calls for the Prohibition of wild animal hunting and feeding sound constantly. But it wasn't until Jan. 26, when the three ministries and commissions issued a joint statement, that the General Administration of Market Supervision, the Ministry of Agriculture and rural areas, and the State Administration of Forestry and grass decided to block the possible source of infection and the route of transmission in order to prevent an epidemic of pneumonia caused by COVID-19, wildlife Trading activities shall be prohibited from the date of the announcement until the national epidemic situation is lifted.

The ban on wildlife trading was welcomed by the International Wildlife Conservation Society (WSC) . "China's ban on the sale of wild animals in markets, restaurants and e-commerce channels should be permanent, " the group said in a statement. But it added that from the content of the statement, the move to ban wildlife is only temporary. Still, Christiane Walzer, executive director of the WSC health program, told China Business News: "We welcome the Chinese government's important and critical step forward. "

The WSC also calls for a global ban on wildlife trade. Walzer told Emerging Infectious Diseases that 70 percent of the world's food supplies come from wildlife. So why would a virus that has long coexisted peacefully with an animal host suddenly attack a new host, a human? Although scientists have not been able to explain the problem, the idea is that these live animal markets encourage the virus to travel back and forth between different species, mutating in the process, the virus could infect humans.

"habitats such as wildlife markets provide a unique opportunity for viruses to spread pathogens from wild hosts, " Walzer told CBN

He also stressed the need not only to invest resources in the discovery of new viruses, but also to identify the epidemiological drivers of the spillover, expansion and spread of infectious diseases. To this end, Walzer told CNBC that there are three ways to tackle this complex global issue. "first, we need to completely close down the market for live animals, " he said. "Second, we need to intensify the crackdown to permanently ban wildlife trade, including cross-border trade, and change the habits of wildlife consumption, especially the consumption of game in cities. "

At present, bats are believed to be the natural host of SARS coronavirus, and SARS coronavirus has also been found in civets in the Chinese wild animal market. Many scientists believe that the bat virus first infected animals such as civets, and then infect people who ate it. After the SARS outbreak, China cracked down hard on the consumer market for civet cats and other species.

But the trade still exists, for example in the south China seafood market. In May 2003, just after the end of the SARS epidemic, the State Forestry Administration of the People's Republic of China in August 2003 immediately identified civets as the first wild animals to be commercially farmed, another 53 species were legalized in the same period.

Multiple successful cross-species transmission of coronaviruses

Dr Mark Denison, an infectious disease specialist who studies coronavirus at Vanderbilt University School of Medicine in Tennessee, said: "coronaviruses have repeatedly demonstrated cross-species detection and have successfully migrated from animal hosts to humans. " The virus needs to mutate multiple times to adapt to its new environment. It must also acquire the ability to invade human cells and evade the human immune system, replicating in the body and spreading to others.

"although the transfer can be described simply as a 'jump' , the process is as complex as jumping over 1,000 hurdles, " said Dr Denison. But he was not surprised by the outbreak. "It's just a matter of time. "

So far, Chinese authorities have released two reports on the state of edible wildlife in China. The most recent report, released in 2013 by the China Wildlife Conservation Society and the Wildlife Rescue Association of the United States, was a survey of the state of edible wildlife in China and public attitudes toward wildlife consumption, although the proportion of wild animals eaten by the public is much lower than in the past, and farmed wild animals have become a major source of food for wild animals, the number of species of wild animals used for business is increasing in some areas, wildlife consumption, especially in southern China, remains robust.

According to the report at the time, October to January of each year is the main season for eating wild animals, and 24,000 valid public questionnaires were received in 16 cities, including Beijing, Shanghai and Guangzhou, while more than 90 per cent of respondents consider wild animal eating illegal or undesirable consumption, nearly 30 per cent said they had eaten wild animals in the past year.

The survey also found that the proportion of non-staple food stores, supermarkets and market stalls selling used wild animals and their products increased by 23 per cent and 18 per cent respectively, compared with the first time in 1999, and the number of wild animal species rose from 53 in 1999 to 80.

Under the influence of the thought of nourishing food, eating wild animals has a long history in China. The majority of the public also believes that eating wild animals serves a nourishing purpose, and some people use eating wild animals as a status symbol, which is the root cause of poaching and wildlife smuggling across the country.

Who is encouraging "venison consumption" ?

"humans get sick from eating wild animals and being exposed to markets that sell them, " Walzer told CNNMONEY. "Meanwhile, the number of wild animals being hunted down and sold is declining rapidly, and the economy and the poor are not benefiting because once there is an outbreak, animals infected with the virus are killed in large numbers, such as poultry and pigs, which in turn drives up the price of meat and poultry, which hurts the economy. "

On the other hand, raising wild animals has also become a way for some remote areas to escape poverty and become rich. For example, bamboo rats and badgers have been raised in large numbers in places such as Guangxi and Jiangxi, and can be sold through e-commerce channels such as Taobao. Some netizens inquired about the relevant e-commerce platforms, showing that these animals have clearly marked prices. For example, the price of a badger is about 1,300 yuan, the price of a civet cat is about 1,500 yuan, and if you buy 500 or more, each animal can be about 100 yuan cheaper.

Some local officials even argue that captive-bred wild animals are not the same as wild animals because they carry different bacteria and viruses. But Walzer explained to China business news: "since it is not clear how the virus infects these wild species, we need to ban all wildlife trade, including farmed bamboo rats. "

Statistics show that there were 5 million wild geese and ducks and 500,000 bamboo rats in Jiangxi province in 2019, while there were no quarantine standards for wild animals such as bamboo rats, snakes and porcupines until 2015.

In the guiding opinions on promoting high-quality development of the forest and grass industry issued by the state forest and grass bureau in 2019, it is stated that "we will standardize the orderly development of special breeding, give full play to the advantages of the ecological environment and species resources in forest areas, focus on non-key protected animals, cultivate a number of special breeding bases and large breeding households, improve breeding capacity, expand population size and increase market supply. ". Social capital should be encouraged to participate in provenance breeding, expansion and large-scale breeding, and to develop domestication and appreciation of wild animals and the processing of fur, meat and eggs."

Industry insiders pointed out that because of the introduction of policies to encourage the supply side, but also to promote the consumer demand increase. Environmentalists are calling for a change in the policy of using wildlife farming for economic gain.
